metadata.name: Archiplex ‚Äî Monochrome #40
metadata.description:
Archiplex Monochrome is a long form generative project, building on the short form Archiplex series. The Archiplex Monochrome algorithm is inspired by Brutalist architecture and design, where expressive forms emerge from the use of textures, materials and structures.

Archiplex Monochrome expands on these Brutalist design elements by floating the central structure of each piece and adding random light sources, introducing unpredictability and elevation to a traditionally structured and grounded art form.

"In this series my subject is the structure: formed yet formless, gravity-bound yet weightless, reflective yet light emitting, unmovable yet malleable."

metadata.name: fields, sketches #57
metadata.description:
The third and final part of our generative sketchbook of ideas for a sculpture garden.

Fields builds off Stan Allen's seminal essay "Field Conditions" in which he laid out a prototypical theory of architectural field schemes. Field Conditions are opposed to figural or object-based compositional strategies and approach a site from a systemic point of view. These fields contain a range of possible wall-types. Some produce enclosures, while others dictate a wandering path.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2022

metadata.description:

metadata.name: Inefficient Ways of Independence #73
metadata.description:
"Inefficient Ways of Independence" is a thought - provoking artwork that explores the relationship between technology and the human experience.

The piece features a collection of iconic symbols of old technology, such as closed - circuit TV cameras, floppy disks, and vintage Mac computers, coupled together by a flow of particles.

The use of human body parts or heads adds a personal touch to the work, highlighting the intimate connection between the individual and technology.

The title "Inefficient Ways of Independence" serves as a commentary on our dependence on technology and the way that it has changed over time.

It also raises questions about our relationship with technology and the limitations that it can impose.

The piece invites the viewer to consider how technology has shaped our lives and to reflect on the consequences of our reliance on it.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT

metadata.name: Cradle #83
metadata.description:
Billions of years old, ancient remains decay across our Solar System. Mere transient visitors to our star, their ephemeral presence on our worlds is embodied in their creations. In the shadow of their megalithic constructions, we wonder what they might have brought to us.

They brought life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'f' - render at full speed
'space' - stop/continue rendering

The image quality gradually improves over time. The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.

metadata.name: pen_tings #100
metadata.description:
A bit of scribbling, a bit of sketching. Experimenting with curves, colors and stop motion animation. Based on particle collision simulation. Inspired by ballpoint pen artworks and scribble drawings.

You can choose between two types of animation*:
- live drawing,
- animation of alternative versions (GIF generation).

Controls (in live view):
Press 's' to save a PNG image.
Press 'n' to generate an alternative version.
Press 'g' to generate a GIF (texture disabled).
Press 'G' to generate a GIF (texture enabled).
Press 'l' to enable live drawing animation.
Press '1-4' to render and save a PNG image (1: 2000x2000, 2: 4000x4000, 3: 6000x6000, 4: 8000x8000).
Pressing 'n', 'g', 'G', 'l', '1-4' reloads the page.

URL parameters (add to the URL in live view: &paramName=paramValue):
- mode - 0: image rendering (default: &mode=0), 1: live drawing animation, 2: GIF generation
- res - resolution; 1: 2000x2000 (default: &res=1), 2: 4000x4000, 3: 6000x6000, 4: 8000x8000; (to render and save a PNG image; only with: mode=0)
- tex - texture; 0: texture disabled, 1: texture enabled (default: &tex=1)
- alt - alternative version; 0: original version (default: &alt=0), [1, 255]: alternative version
- gres - GIF resolution; 1: 480x480, 2: 640x640, 3: 768x768, 4: 1080x1080 (default: &gres=4), 5: 1200x1200; (only with: mode=2)
- glen - GIF length in seconds; [1, 6], 2: 2 s (default: &glen=2); (only with: mode=2)
- gfps - GIF fps; 1: 5 fps, 2: 10 fps (default: &gfps=2); (only with: mode=2)

Image rendering (especially in high resolution) may take some time, please wait.
GIF generation (regardless of the selected resolution) may take several minutes, please be patient.
Chrome browser (desktop version) recommended.

-----
(*) WARNING: LIVE DRAWING ANIMATION AND GENERATED GIF (ESPECIALLY) CAN BE EPILEPTIC TRIGGERS. GIF GENERATION IS AN EXPERIMENTAL FEATURE.

Made with p5.js, matter.js (2D physics¬†engine) and Trigfills (cross browser trigonometric functions consistency), see LICENSE.md.

varmaxart, February 2023

metadata.name: Foundations #139
metadata.description:
In march of this year, I started working on a new series involving multi-layering, and overriding shapes. Drawing and playing with colors and opacity.
It started with squares and grid, it then involved deformations, and circles and other experimentations.
This path fits with my artistic generative approach: rather than having a completely predefined idea, I start with a simple concept that evolves during creation. Then surprises happened, and I embraced them.

But this year was not like any other: 2022 has gifted me with a new birthday, the one of my son.

Over the past twelve months, I‚Äôve watched him discovering the world surrounding him, learning and trying new things, laughing, or getting frustrated, sad or happy‚Ä¶
While learning to become a parent, I‚Äôve been in an introspection phase where I questioned what it means to be ‚Äúa father‚Äù. What impact will I have on my son, consciously or not?

‚ÄúFoundations‚Äù takes shape in this context: 2 humans trying and exploring while being inspired by each other.
This series is a first of a set of at least 3, that illustrates an idea of what is an ‚ÄúIdentity‚Äù, and what makes us who we are.

The foundations of an identity are laid in the first days of a child‚Äôs life. They will be influenced by many factors; including parenting, cultural environment, life experiences‚Ä¶ 
Of course, as humans we are in constant evolution; life happens, sometimes for the best, sometimes for the worst, and our personality will be impacted‚Ä¶
But this will be a topic for another time. 


Today, we are at the start.

metadata.name: The Beauty of Discord #184
metadata.description:
This experimental artwork is a unique blend of human and machine inputs, showcasing the potential for collaboration between the two in the creative process. The human component of the piece is evident in the deliberate composition, choice of color, and the use of painting algorithms. Meanwhile, the machine component is represented by two powerful AI technologies. The first, ChatGPT3, generated a thought-provoking poem about the galaxies and cosmos, serving as the inspiration for the piece. The second, DALL-E 2, then used this poem as a prompt to create a stunning AI image, bringing the cosmic themes to life in a realistic and captivating way.

The combination of these two AI technologies, along with the human touch in the painting algorithms and composition, creates an artwork that is truly one-of-a-kind. The final product is not only visually stunning, but it also serves as a glimpse into the future of humanity and the possibilities of AI collaboration in art. The artwork is a testament to the beauty that can result from a seemingly discordant combination of human and machine inputs, and it invites us to consider the impact of technology on the creative process and the role of the human artist in the age of AI.

Artist notes:
Press s to download high-res images.
Press a to see the AI-generated image.
Press g to switch back to the paint.

Read more on the medium website:
shorturl.at/bkqW8

metadata.name: BRUTALIST MOVEMENT #89
metadata.description:
Inspired and fascinated by Brutalism, Modernism and Bauhaus, I've started to explore the deeper connections of architecture using pixel art in a clean, minimalistic and unique way.

The BRUTALIST MOVEMENT project represents the next step in this process. It's an animated generative experiment that focuses on finding the simplest and fewest components that - when generated randomly - always create structures resembling buildings: from small modern houses through industrial facilities to gigantic brutalist monuments.

This resulted in 4 main components: Base, Extension, Gap and Window. These entities are used randomly to create Blocks that form the final structure. 
The whole process is also strictly accompanied by 4 distinct components to hold colors and to be set by randomly chosen palettes: Sky, Sun, Shadow, Window.

Features consist of a mixture of the above components.

The project is animated to show how the buildings come to life. It's also a nice way to show what's going on in the background, because from time to time a bigger block would surely hide interesting smaller ones :) 

Press these keys:
's' - to download a larger resolution PNG
'n' - to shuffle through the 'depth' of Blocks, aka placing them from front to back and vice versa. This is a nice feature to show structures hidden by others and also a cool way to create iterations inside the iteration - sub-iterations - we can say :)
'r' - to reset the Blocks' depths to default

Please note:
Everything you see is generated, animated and drawn real-time. No layered transparent PNGs, PFP or similar!

Have fun and inspiration!
